description: From Old French prelat, from Medieval Latin praelatus, from past participle of praeferre (“to prefer”).

entries.meaning: A clergyman of high rank and authority, having jurisdiction over an area or a group of people; normally a bishop.

verbs.description: prelate (third-person singular simple present prelates, present participle prelating, simple past and past participle prelated)

examples: Right prelating is busy labouring, and not lording.
